<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Penstemon heterodoxus </i>grows in open rocky areas with stems 65 cm high. The leaves are entire, sometimes folded lengthwise, and usually not clasping around the stems. Many deep purple flowers occur in one or more clusters on glandular inflorescence stalks. Plants may produce extensive mats. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Penstemon heterodoxus </i>is a plant of the mountain meadows and slopes from the Klamath Mountains south to Inyo Mountains and into Nevada. Stands are usually on the edges of meadows with a variety of herb species; they are typically mesic to dry, open and nonsod- forming. The soils are typically disturbed by frost heave or by animals such as gophers and horses (Benedict 1983). This alliance may indicate disturbance conditions for several alliances. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stand descriptions come from the Sierra Nevada (M261E) at subalpine elevations. Major and Taylor (1977) described an <i>Antennaria media</i>-<i>Penstemon heterodoxus</i> association from the Carson Pass area. Benedict (1983) recognized a <i>Penstemon heterodoxus-Achillea millefolium</i> association in the Mount Whitney area of Sequoia National Park. While Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf (2007) treated these as unranked associations in their review of alpine vegetation in the state, we recognize them in this provisional alliance. Also, Keeler-Wolf et al. (2003b) denoted a <i>Carex filifolia-Penstemon heterodoxus</i> association in the <i>Carex filifolia</i> alliance for stands in the Yosemite National Park. We need further sampling and analysis to understand more fully these moist meadow complexes in the Sierra Nevada. </div>
</div>

	

    
